WEBVTT

00:04.960 --> 00:07.167
(BABY CRYING)

00:07.240 --> 00:09.208
(SPEAKS CHINESE DIALECT)

01:25.520 --> 01:27.170
Sir, this is her.

01:29.000 --> 01:30.445
The girl who tells fortunes?

01:45.320 --> 01:47.448
(FAINT WHISPERING)

02:03.400 --> 02:06.563
They're doing a magic spell.
To make it win a race.

02:13.840 --> 02:15.808
The horse's name is Monaghan Boy.

02:16.160 --> 02:18.242
Kempton. 3:00. Monday.

02:18.840 --> 02:21.684
You ladies have a bet yourselves,
but don't tell anyone else.

02:27.960 --> 02:29.849
(TH EME MUSIC PLAYING)

02:47.600 --> 02:50.524
MAN: And Abraham
made his home in a cave.

02:50.600 --> 02:54.571
But it was good. Because
God resided there with him.

02:55.280 --> 03:01.128
You see, children, God does not care
if you live in a slum, or in a mansion.

03:01.720 --> 03:05.770
God does not care if you are rich,
or you are poor...

03:15.040 --> 03:16.041
Morning, sir.

03:25.720 --> 03:26.721
Morning, Mr Shelby.

04:10.440 --> 04:12.044
- Come on, lad.
- Good day, sir.

04:13.480 --> 04:15.801
- Morning, Mr Shelby.
- Sir.

04:19.720 --> 04:20.801
MAN: Good day, Mr Shelby.

04:31.600 --> 04:32.601
Finn?

04:35.360 --> 04:36.850
Arthur's mad as hell.

04:41.000 --> 04:43.207
What does a 10-year-old
know about hell? Eh?

04:43.440 --> 04:44.805
I'm 11 Sunday.

04:51.520 --> 04:53.329
(MEN CALLING OUT)

04:56.640 --> 04:57.721
I'm looking for Tommy.

04:57.800 --> 05:00.724
BOOKIE: Get your bets in now
for the 2:30 at Kempton.

05:00.800 --> 05:02.643
Right, what we got on Percy Piper?

05:02.720 --> 05:06.281
Piper going well in the soft, lads.
Down to fours.

05:06.360 --> 05:07.646
Fours.

05:07.720 --> 05:10.200
- Okay, Monaghan Boy?
- Wanna push that down, mate.

05:10.280 --> 05:11.281
Two to one, still.

05:18.080 --> 05:20.481
Two to one. Get your bets in now.

05:20.560 --> 05:23.040
What do you say? We got Topper in,
he's an old favourite.

05:23.120 --> 05:24.485
Four to one.

05:27.080 --> 05:28.605
Tommy! Tommy!

05:28.880 --> 05:31.121
Tommy, look at the book.
just look.

05:31.600 --> 05:33.125
- ARTHUR: Tommy!
- All on Monaghan Boy.

05:33.200 --> 05:34.884
- Good work, john.
- Tommy!

05:35.640 --> 05:37.165
Get in here. Now.

05:38.480 --> 05:39.845
BOOKIE: That'll be six pennies, nipper.

05:40.360 --> 05:41.885
That's ten bob you'll see for that.

05:50.920 --> 05:55.244
Now, you were seen doing the
powder trick down at Garrison Courts.

05:56.200 --> 05:57.201
Times are hard.

05:58.160 --> 05:59.650
People need a reason to lay a bet.

06:00.320 --> 06:01.446
There was a Chinese.

06:02.240 --> 06:04.208
The washerwomen say she's a witch.

06:05.280 --> 06:08.011
- It helps them believe.
- We don't mess with Chinese.

06:08.480 --> 06:12.690
- Look at the book.
- Chinese have cutters of their own.

06:13.120 --> 06:14.610
We agreed, Arthur.

06:15.360 --> 06:17.761
I'm taking charge
of drumming up their money.

06:20.640 --> 06:22.449
What if Monaghan Boy wins, Tommy?

06:23.480 --> 06:24.811
You fixing races now?

06:25.640 --> 06:28.883
Do you have permission from Billy Kimber
to be fixing races? Hmm?

06:30.880 --> 06:32.370
And what's got into you?

06:33.680 --> 06:38.129
You think we can take on
the Chinese and Billy Kimber?

06:38.360 --> 06:42.251
- Billy's got a bloody army!
- I think, Arthur.

06:43.360 --> 06:44.771
That's what I do.

06:48.520 --> 06:49.760
I think.

06:51.040 --> 06:53.168
So that you don't have to.

06:57.200 --> 06:58.611
There's news from Belfast.

07:04.720 --> 07:07.530
I'm calling a family council tonight
at 8:0Â®.

07:07.840 --> 07:08.966
I want all of us there.

07:09.840 --> 07:11.126
You hear me?

07:11.520 --> 07:12.931
There's trouble coming.

07:13.040 --> 07:14.849
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

07:58.720 --> 08:00.529
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS)

08:12.520 --> 08:14.727
All right, shut up now.
Shut up.

08:16.800 --> 08:20.885
Comrades, we're here today
to take a vote on strike action.

08:20.960 --> 08:22.041
MEN: Yes!

08:23.360 --> 08:25.169
But before we have a
show of hands for that,

08:26.600 --> 08:29.251
let's have a show of hands from
all those who fought in France.

08:29.720 --> 08:32.530
All those who stood side by side
with your comrades,

08:33.000 --> 08:34.729
and watched your comrades fall.

08:35.520 --> 08:37.124
Raise your hands.

08:41.400 --> 08:44.404
The blood shed on Flanders Fields.

08:44.960 --> 08:46.849
The sweat of your brows.

08:48.040 --> 08:49.485
Who reaps the rewards?

08:50.120 --> 08:51.121
IS it you?

08:51.200 --> 08:52.565
- No, no.
- No!

08:52.640 --> 08:53.687
Is it your wives?

08:53.760 --> 08:55.125
- No, no.
- No, no.

08:55.240 --> 08:56.969
Well, who then?
Do they stand among us?

08:57.040 --> 08:58.041
"No!
"No!

08:58.200 --> 09:01.807
Or do they sit at home,
comfortable, with a full belly?

09:02.200 --> 09:07.127
While you scrape to find enough
to put shoes on your children's feet!

09:07.200 --> 09:10.522
And what is the reward they offer you
for your sacrifices made?

09:11.520 --> 09:13.761
A fucking cut in your wages!

09:14.040 --> 09:15.201
That is your reward!

09:16.360 --> 09:18.681
Raise a hand,
all those who want to strike!

09:18.760 --> 09:21.491
- Yes! Yes!
- Yes! Yes!

10:14.120 --> 10:15.326
On the house, Mr Shelby.

10:36.160 --> 10:37.650
- I'll take a mild.
- Right.

10:57.960 --> 10:58.961
Cheers, Thomas.

11:00.040 --> 11:01.041
Good health to you.

11:07.440 --> 11:08.566
Crown of a prince.

11:12.520 --> 11:14.921
- Soon to be king, I'd bet.
- You don't bet.

11:15.720 --> 11:18.530
No, but these past few days
I've been speculating.

11:22.840 --> 11:23.841
About what?

11:24.880 --> 11:26.848
One of my union comrades has a sister.

11:27.200 --> 11:29.771
Works in the telegraph office
at the BSA factory.

11:30.640 --> 11:32.130
She says, over the past week,

11:32.200 --> 11:34.521
they've had messages coming up
from London to the brass.

11:35.360 --> 11:36.850
From Winston Churchill himself.

11:42.080 --> 11:43.650
Something about a robbery.

11:44.960 --> 11:47.531
A robbery of national significance,
it's said.

11:50.280 --> 11:52.009
She found a list of names

11:52.080 --> 11:54.003
left in the telegraph machine.

11:55.800 --> 11:58.724
And on that list was your name
and my name together.

12:01.640 --> 12:03.369
What kind of a list would
have the name of a communist

12:03.440 --> 12:05.408
and the name of a bookmaker
side by side?

12:10.160 --> 12:13.801
Perhaps it's a list of men
who give false hope to the poor.

12:15.160 --> 12:17.561
The only difference between
you and me, Freddie,

12:17.640 --> 12:19.847
is that, sometimes...

12:19.920 --> 12:21.490
my horses stand a chance of winning.

12:29.440 --> 12:30.726
You know, there are days -

12:30.800 --> 12:32.564
when I hear about
the cuttings and beatings -

12:32.640 --> 12:35.530
that I really wish I'd let you
take that bullet in France.

12:37.360 --> 12:40.443
Believe me,
there are nights I wish you had.

12:43.520 --> 12:44.681
Hey!

12:49.240 --> 12:50.366
They're gonna kill me!

12:50.440 --> 12:52.807
On three! One, two, three, go!

12:54.920 --> 12:56.331
Breathe, Danny. Breathe!

12:56.400 --> 12:58.721
They're gonna kill me!
They're gonna kill me!

12:59.080 --> 13:02.129
- They're gonna kill me!
- Danny! Danny, Danny, you're home.

13:02.200 --> 13:03.725
We're all home in England.

13:03.800 --> 13:05.131
You're not in France.

13:05.600 --> 13:08.490
You're not an artillery shell, Danny,
you're a man.

13:08.560 --> 13:09.721
Eh?

13:09.800 --> 13:12.690
You're not a whizz-bang,
you're a human being, Danny.

13:13.080 --> 13:15.686
You're all right.
You're all right.

13:16.280 --> 13:17.327
You're all right.

13:17.720 --> 13:19.370
Up, UP!

13:20.320 --> 13:21.321
(WHIMPERS)

13:23.320 --> 13:24.446
It's all right.

13:25.520 --> 13:26.521
It's all right.

13:29.520 --> 13:30.726
Oh, hell.

13:31.240 --> 13:32.480
Did I do it again?

13:33.920 --> 13:35.524
You did it again, Danny.

13:38.800 --> 13:40.768
You gotta stop doing this, man.

13:42.120 --> 13:44.282
- He's all right.
- Oh God, Mr Shelby, I'm sorry.

13:44.360 --> 13:45.361
It's all right.

13:45.880 --> 13:47.803
- You go home to your wife now, Danny.
- Yeah.

13:48.240 --> 13:50.368
And get all that smoke and mud
out of your head, eh?

13:50.640 --> 13:53.007
Yes, Mr Shelby. I'm sorry.

13:54.200 --> 13:55.201
Go on.

13:59.760 --> 14:02.206
Mr Shelby, you have to do
something about him.

14:02.400 --> 14:03.686
Damn right, Harry.

14:03.760 --> 14:06.286
You pay the Peaky Blinders
a lot of money for protection.

14:07.960 --> 14:10.008
You're the law around here now, Tommy,
aren't you?

14:11.120 --> 14:13.088
Maybe you should put a bullet
in Danny Whizz-Bang's head

14:13.160 --> 14:15.162
like they do with mad horses.

14:17.440 --> 14:20.125
Maybe you'll have to put a bullet
in my head someday, too.

14:30.440 --> 14:32.249
Bring the bill to the Peaky Blinders.

14:32.720 --> 14:33.721
We'll take care of it.

14:53.720 --> 14:55.370
Look at the gun.

14:56.880 --> 14:58.928
- Recognise it?
- Mmm.

15:00.560 --> 15:01.607
(CRIES OUT)

15:01.680 --> 15:03.603
- Fuck!
- Get up off your arse, you mumping pig.

15:03.680 --> 15:06.286
Aunt Poll, what the fuck
did you do that for?

15:06.800 --> 15:09.326
Finn was playing with this
this afternoon by the cut.

15:09.400 --> 15:11.767
It was loaded.
Nearly blew Ada's tits off.

15:12.680 --> 15:13.841
It must have fell out of me pocket.

15:13.960 --> 15:16.042
He said he found it on the
sideboard of the betting shop.

15:16.160 --> 15:17.286
With bullets in it.

15:18.120 --> 15:19.121
I...

15:19.800 --> 15:20.801
I must have been drunk.

15:22.600 --> 15:23.726
When are you not drunk?

15:24.040 --> 15:25.963
Look, Aunt Polly, I'm sorry.

15:26.720 --> 15:28.529
(STAMMERS) I'm... I'm sorry.

15:30.120 --> 15:31.849
We'll keep this between ourselves

15:31.920 --> 15:34.491
if you swear not to leave guns
lying around.

15:38.040 --> 15:41.203
Look, I know having four kids
without a woman is hard,

15:41.280 --> 15:43.089
but my boot's harder.
Now come on, were late.

15:45.000 --> 15:46.240
Right!

15:46.320 --> 15:49.802
I've called this family meeting because
I've got some very important news.

15:50.720 --> 15:53.724
Scudboat and Lovelock
got back from Belfast last night.

15:54.880 --> 15:57.247
They were buying a stallion
to cover their mares.

15:58.120 --> 16:00.521
They were in a pub on the
Shankhill Road yesterday,

16:00.760 --> 16:03.604
and in that pub there was a copper.

16:04.480 --> 16:06.244
Handing out these.

16:09.040 --> 16:11.805
"If you're over five feet
and can fight, come to Birmingham."

16:13.520 --> 16:17.650
They're recruiting Protestant Irishmen
to come over here as Special.

16:17.800 --> 16:20.280
- To do what?
- To clean up the city, Ada.

16:20.920 --> 16:22.206
He's the Chief Inspector.

16:23.400 --> 16:26.927
The last four years, he's been
clearing the IRA out of Belfast.

16:27.280 --> 16:28.850
How do you know so bloody much?

16:29.360 --> 16:31.328
'Cause I asked the coppers
on our payroll.

16:31.880 --> 16:33.041
And why didn't you tell me?

16:35.360 --> 16:36.361
I'm telling you.

16:38.840 --> 16:40.410
So why are they sending him
to Birmingham?

16:40.720 --> 16:43.166
Well, there's been all these
bloody strikes at the BSA.

16:43.480 --> 16:44.925
And the Austin works, lately.

16:45.840 --> 16:47.729
Now the papers
are talking about sedition.

16:48.520 --> 16:49.521
And revolution.

16:50.440 --> 16:52.010
I reckon it's communists he's after.

16:52.400 --> 16:54.528
So this copper's gonna
leave us alone, right?

16:55.520 --> 16:58.569
There are Irishmen in Green Lanes
who left Belfast to get away from him.

16:59.200 --> 17:02.044
They say Catholic men who crossed him
used to disappear in the night.

17:02.240 --> 17:03.401
Yeah, but we ain't IRA.

17:04.200 --> 17:05.770
We bloody fought for the King.

17:06.720 --> 17:08.131
Anyway, we're Peaky Blinders.

17:08.560 --> 17:09.800
We're not scared of coppers.

17:09.880 --> 17:11.689
- He's right.
- If they come for us,

17:11.880 --> 17:13.369
we'll cut them a smile each.

17:14.160 --> 17:15.650
So, Arthur. Is that it?

17:16.960 --> 17:18.325
ARTHUR:
What do you think, Aunt Poll?

17:19.079 --> 17:20.650
This family does everything open.

17:22.319 --> 17:24.242
You've nothing more to say
to this meeting, Thomas?

17:25.160 --> 17:26.161
No.

17:27.000 --> 17:28.365
Nothing that's women's business.

17:28.640 --> 17:30.642
This whole bloody enterprise
was women's business

17:30.720 --> 17:32.370
while you boys were away at war.

17:33.360 --> 17:34.361
What's changed?

17:35.640 --> 17:36.641
We came back.

17:37.360 --> 17:40.091
And the Lord will smite the unholy

17:40.160 --> 17:41.844
when the greatjudgement comes.

17:42.400 --> 17:44.402
And judgment is coming, my friends.

17:44.840 --> 17:47.923
Judgment is coming to this wicked city.

17:48.000 --> 17:52.528
And your wickedness
and your fornication will be revealed.

17:52.960 --> 17:55.566
You cannot hide from the Creator.

17:56.160 --> 17:59.562
You cannot hide
from the Almighty himself.

18:00.040 --> 18:01.724
The Creator sees all.

18:02.400 --> 18:05.449
You cannot hide
from the true and living God.

18:05.520 --> 18:07.409
Get off with ya!

18:11.720 --> 18:12.721
Ahh!

18:17.080 --> 18:18.206
Fuck off.

18:30.040 --> 18:31.405
(CHILD SHOUTING)

18:31.840 --> 18:33.763
That's it. I don't go any further.

18:36.440 --> 18:38.761
(CHILDREN SHOUTING)

18:51.000 --> 18:53.651
I have ten minutes.
What do you want?

18:58.320 --> 18:59.845
An explanation.

19:03.560 --> 19:07.007
Always been able to tell
when you're hiding something.

19:08.880 --> 19:10.484
People round here talk.

19:11.320 --> 19:13.049
Some of them work at the BSA.

19:14.280 --> 19:16.328
I've been talking to the wives
of factory hands.

19:16.400 --> 19:19.529
Detectives have been asking questions
in the proofing shops.

19:21.280 --> 19:24.682
Nothing happens in that factory
without you knowing about it.

19:25.360 --> 19:26.361
Speak.

19:27.640 --> 19:29.563
God and Aunt Polly are listening.

19:39.800 --> 19:41.564
It was meant to be routine.

19:44.440 --> 19:47.171
I had a buyer in London
for some motorcycles.

19:48.400 --> 19:51.722
I asked my men to steal me four bikes
with petrol engines.

19:54.200 --> 19:56.089
I'm guessing my men were drunk.

19:56.880 --> 19:59.884
<i>There's a still inside the factory
makes tram line gin.</i>

20:03.840 --> 20:05.922
<i>They picked up the wrong fucking crate.</i>

20:07.480 --> 20:10.324
<i>The boys dropped it
at Charlie Strong's yard, as agreed.</i>

20:11.160 --> 20:15.370
<i>Must have taken it from the
proofing bay, instead of the export bay.</i>

20:20.880 --> 20:23.201
Holy sweet baby of Mary.

20:23.520 --> 20:26.251
Inside we found 25 Lewis machine guns,

20:27.160 --> 20:28.889
10,000 rounds of ammunition,

20:30.040 --> 20:34.090
50 semi-automatic rifles,
200 pistols with shells.

20:34.320 --> 20:35.321
Jesus, Tommy.

20:36.800 --> 20:37.881
All bound for Libya.

20:39.760 --> 20:42.650
Sitting right there
in Charlie Strong's yard.

20:45.560 --> 20:46.891
Tell me you threw them in the cut.

20:48.480 --> 20:50.209
We put them in the stables
out of the rain.

20:51.120 --> 20:53.407
The guns hadn't been greased yet.

20:57.680 --> 20:59.523
So that's why they sent a cop
from Belfast?

21:00.880 --> 21:02.291
Maybe, maybe not.

21:04.800 --> 21:08.282
Thomas, you're a bookmaker,
a robber, a fighting man.

21:08.360 --> 21:09.930
You're not a fool.

21:10.000 --> 21:12.844
You sell those guns to anyone who has
use to them, you will hang.

21:12.920 --> 21:13.921
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

21:19.280 --> 21:20.805
Dump them somewhere
the police can find them.

21:21.720 --> 21:24.007
Maybe if they know they haven't fallen
into the wrong hands,

21:24.080 --> 21:25.809
this might blow over.

21:26.960 --> 21:29.327
- Tell Charlie to dump them tonight.
- No.

21:30.080 --> 21:32.447
He won't move contraband
under a full moon.

21:32.880 --> 21:34.723
Three days until it wanes.

21:35.600 --> 21:36.601
Then you'll do the right thing?

21:40.240 --> 21:41.685
You have your mother's common sense.

21:42.640 --> 21:43.721
But your father's devilment.

21:45.200 --> 21:46.804
I see them fighting.

21:47.880 --> 21:49.405
Let your mother win.

22:39.200 --> 22:41.009
I got tickets for the penny crush.

22:41.280 --> 22:42.850
They're showing a Tom Mix picture.

22:44.240 --> 22:46.322
I'm not in the mood
for the pictures tonight, Ada.

22:46.400 --> 22:49.290
Well, I'm not doing it here again.
I got covered in mud last time.

22:49.640 --> 22:50.687
Let's just walk a bit.

22:51.280 --> 22:53.487
If we go down as far as Greet,
we could go to a pub.

22:54.760 --> 22:56.444
Your brothers have friends in Greet.

22:56.960 --> 22:59.008
They have friends everywhere,
we'd have to walk to London.

22:59.200 --> 23:02.204
I'm with you 'cause you're the
only man round here not scared of them.

23:02.880 --> 23:04.370
Oh, I'm scared of them all right.

23:04.920 --> 23:07.207
But you love me
more than you fear them, right?

23:09.000 --> 23:11.002
I don't want to be
always sneaking about.

23:12.520 --> 23:14.727
- Soon, we'll tell them.
- When?

23:19.280 --> 23:20.691
How did the family meeting go?

23:24.120 --> 23:25.121
UsuaL

23:25.720 --> 23:27.609
- There's a new copper coming.
- I heard.

23:27.880 --> 23:28.927
Mmm.

23:29.000 --> 23:31.048
And Tommy says
he's after the likes of you.

23:31.680 --> 23:35.651
So maybe you should burn your books
and stop making speeches.

23:36.400 --> 23:37.526
Oh, my Ada.

23:38.360 --> 23:42.001
The only princess of the Royal Family
of the kingdom of Small Heath.

23:42.840 --> 23:45.525
I'm just a poor communist frog
with a big mouth.

23:50.000 --> 23:51.525
Give me a kiss, Princess Ada.

23:51.720 --> 23:52.721
(ADA GIGGLES)

24:35.120 --> 24:36.929
I'm here about the job as a barmaid.

24:40.160 --> 24:42.162
- Are you mad?
- Am I what?

24:42.480 --> 24:45.768
- Do you know about this place?
- I saw it in an advertisement.

24:46.320 --> 24:48.687
- Job's been filled.
- It was in yesterday's paper.

24:49.400 --> 24:52.165
Believe me, love,
I'm doing you a favour.

24:52.320 --> 24:54.800
I'm not asking for favours,
I'm asking for employment.

24:58.720 --> 25:01.485
You're too...nice.

25:02.600 --> 25:04.443
- How would you know?
- And too pretty.

25:05.360 --> 25:06.725
They'd have you up against a wall.

25:07.640 --> 25:10.723
I have experience. And references.

25:15.840 --> 25:18.650
- What part of Ireland are you from?
- Galway.

25:18.880 --> 25:19.881
Oh.

25:20.480 --> 25:21.481
I worked in Dublin.

25:22.880 --> 25:24.291
Me mother was from Galway.

25:27.960 --> 25:28.961
You're too pretty.

25:29.760 --> 25:30.761
Vvatch.

25:32.000 --> 25:33.411
And listen.

25:35.480 --> 25:37.767
<i># I wish I was</i>

25:38.400 --> 25:41.529
<i># In Carrickfergus</i>

25:42.200 --> 25:44.328
<i># Only for nights</i>

25:44.720 --> 25:46.802
<i># In Ballygrand</i>

25:47.320 --> 25:50.529
<i># I would swim over</i>

25:50.880 --> 25:53.690
<i># The deepest ocean</i>

25:54.520 --> 25:56.488
<i># The deepest ocean</i>

25:56.800 --> 25:58.962
<i># My love to find</i>

